message: I agree with Dolmagray and all the other recent edits.
Reverting is taking place here without the consensus of all those participating in the talkpage discussion. That's not acceptable.
If for everything else, there should be a citation for "linguistics being the study of natural language" too.
Everybody's side of the argument is clearly mentioned in this. If this version is not retained, it most definitely is censorship.
One minute, what is "artistic literature"? And coherent texts? Who studies incoherent texts, then? Vets? :D
hmmm, that's a nice para actually, which includes semiotics. Just needs some more literature to it, though.
/* This article on evolution */ new section
There has been support of mine on the talkpage: please look at it carefully. Various people have agreed with it: Orson, etc.
As stated below. There are enough number of people arguing over this, yet.
Consensus is not arrived upon by simply stating a contradicting point on the talk page, because then I would have won the argument eons ago.
I think the line about "other approaches" deserves a citation more than the related fields.
There are a fair number of people on the talkpage who believe that the "other" view needs to be represented in the article as well, and that the study of literature is important to the study of lang.
The consensus was to replace the word scientific with the word systematic, because the latter encompasses the former. The debate includes the issue of humanist methodology and non-natural languages.
I don't think you are reading the talkpage? We have arrived at a consensus over the use of the word 'systematic'.
